question:
Let the quadratic function \( f(x) = \frac{1}{2}(x-10)^2 \) and let \( n \) be a positive integer. Define \( a_n \) as follows, depending on the convergence or divergence of the improper integral \( \int^{\infty}_{1} (f(n))^t dt \).

\[
a_n = \begin{cases} 
\int^{\infty}_{1} (f(n))^t dt, & \text{if } \int^{\infty}_{1} (f(n))^t dt \text{ converges} \\
0, & \text{if } \int^{\infty}_{1} (f(n))^t dt \text{ diverges}
\end{cases}
\]

Find the numerator of \(\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} a_n\).

Find the solution to the following system of linear congruences.

\[
\begin{cases} 
8x \equiv 4 \pmod{22} \\ 
3x \equiv 5 \pmod{25} 
\end{cases}
\]

Find a function with the numerator being the integer \( a \) and the denominator being the value of \( b \) such that the congruence \( x \equiv 25^{99} \pmod{19 \cdot 13} \) becomes equivalent to the system of congruences 

\[
\begin{cases} 
x \equiv a \pmod{19} \\ 
x \equiv b \pmod{13} 
\end{cases}
\]

given that \( 0 \leq a < 19, 0 \leq b < 13, 0 \leq x < 247 \).

Two random variables \( X \) and \( Y \) are independent and both have the same probability density function given by 
\[ 
f(t) = 
\begin{cases} 
2t, & 0 \leq t \leq 1 \\ 
0, & \text{otherwise} 
\end{cases} 
\]
Calculate the probability that \( Y \) is between \( X \) and \( X^2 \).

Let \(X\) and \(Y\) be two continuous random variables with the joint probability density function \(f(x, y)\)

\[ f(x, y) = \begin{cases} 
\frac{1}{5} xy(1-x+y), & 0<x<1, 1<y<3 \\
0, & \text{otherwise} 
\end{cases} \]

Find the marginal probability density function \(f_Y(y)\) of \(Y\), and use this to determine the conditional probability density function \(f_{X|Y}(x|2)\) of \(X\) given \(Y=2\) and the conditional expectation \(E[X | Y=2]\).

The sequence \(\{x_n\}\) satisfies 

\((4+x_1+\cdots+x_n)(x_1+\cdots+x_{n+1})=1\)

for every positive integer \(n\), and \(x_1=1\). Find the value of \([\frac{x_{100}}{x_{101}}]^2\). (Here, \([x]\) denotes the greatest integer less than or equal to \(x\).)
